    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-09-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="418"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                <head>418. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="from"
                        >Kennedy</persName> to Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                        type="to">McNamara</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d418fn0">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, RG 330, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss> Files: <gloss
                            target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 66 A 3542, Cuba 342.18 (31 Jan 1962).
                        Secret. A stamped note on the source text indicates that <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> saw the memorandum. An unsigned
                        copy of this memorandum is in the <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files, Countries Series,
                        Cuba, General, 9/62.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-09-07">September 7, 1962</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I would appreciate an up-to-date brief report on the number of Cubans who joined
                    the U.S. armed forces as a result of our interest in this <pb facs="1082"
                        n="1050" xml:id="pg_1050"/> matter last year, and an idea of how many
                    applied who were not acceptable.</p>
                <p>I would also like your reaction and the reaction of the Joint Chiefs of Staff to
                    the formation of a Cuban brigade in which we would enlist Cuban nationals for a
                    period of six to nine months for training, with no guarantee, of course, that
                    they would be returned to Cuba, but a promise that if the need arose, a Cuban
                    brigade would be used. It is my understanding that to make a success of this
                    brigade we would have to alter the present physical standards for Army service
                    so that a greater number of Cubans who might want to participate could be
                    included.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">John F. Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
